CHANGELOG: Version 2.1.5

+ README minor fixes

plow*: move --no-color to early options parsing

Command line parsing is a 3-step process. Each plow script define
two sets of options: early ones (for example -h/--help) and main ones
(for example -t/--timeout). Remaining options are matched with union
of all modules options

Currently when user enters a wrong command line, error message is
colored only when it concerns a module option. By moving --no-color switch
to the first (early) set, main options errors could be colored as well.

<shell>
$ plowdown -t
plowdown (-t): argument required                 // red color error message
$ plowdown --no-color -t
plowdown (-t): argument required
</shell>

As early options are switches without argument (--help, --longhelp, --version, --modules),
there is no color message issue... except for --plowsharerc switch (which requires a filename argument)!

BTW, do you know this trick to get argument type:
<shell>
$ plowdown  -t
plowdown (-t): argument required
$ plowdown  -t=
plowdown (-t): positive integer expected
</shell>
